= Chapter 7: The Muffled Path
\
The great iron alarm bell didn’t ring for long.

On its sixth CLANG, a massive, shadow-covered fist slammed into the belfry tower. The metal cracked, and the ringing cut off into a sharp, agonizing screech before tumbling into the streets below.

Suddenly, a terrifying silence fell over Luminos-Vara—but it wasn't a peaceful silence. It was a suffocating, heavy quiet broken only by the panicked screams of citizens fleeing their homes. Down in the streets, the darkness was winning. The blue soul lanterns were flickering out one by one as the ink-black skulk climbed the lampposts, choking the flames.

From Master Elian’s balcony, Valen watched a crowd of terrified citizens sprint down a main walkway. Behind them, a corrupted Warden emerged from the shadows. Its stone skin was now completely veined with pulsing teal light, and its bone-white rib cage was pulled wide open.

The Warden raised its massive arms, its chest crystal flaring with a violent energy.

BOOM!

A sonic wave of pure, concentrated sound exploded from its chest. The blast hit the deepslate ground, shattering the stone blocks and sending a shockwave that knocked the fleeing citizens off their feet.

"They’re attacking anything that makes a sound," Valen whispered, his hands gripping the balcony railing. "Every scream, every footstep, every falling piece of stone just tells them exactly where we are."

Master Elian was trembling, holding a crate of redstone repeaters that was now totally useless. "My city... my beautiful city. Valen, how do we stop them? We can’t fight an army of our own creations!"

Valen looked from the rampaging monsters down to his own hands. He still had his golden tuning fork tucked into his belt. "We have to close the Grand Gateway. If we break the connection, the heartbeat from the other side will stop, and maybe the Wardens will shut down. But the whole central plaza is covered in skulk. We’ll never make it across the cobblestone without waking every sensor in the city."

Then, Valen’s eyes darted to the corner of Elian's workshop.

Resting in a corner were several heavy crates from the surface world, filled with blocks of soft, thick wool and rolls of woven carpet used for trading.

Valen’s mind flashed back to the way the skulk absorbed sound. It feeds on vibrations, he thought. But what if we use something that suffocates vibrations entirely?

"Master Elian, help me with these carpets!" Valen yelled, dropping to his knees and dragging a massive roll of gray wool out of a crate.

"Carpets?" Elian blinked, utterly confused. "Valen, this is no time for interior decorating!"

"It’s not decoration, it’s armor!" Valen said, slinging a heavy roll over his shoulder. "Wool doesn't make a sound when you step on it. It swallows the vibration. If we line the streets with wool, we can walk right past the sensors!"

Moments later, the old master and the young apprentice stepped out of the tower's heavy doors.

The air in the alleyway was thick with the scent of sulfur and old moss. Just ten blocks away, a Skulk Sensor sat on top of a stone wall, its dark tendrils twitching in the air, listening.

Valen held his breath. He unrolled a long strip of gray carpet, laying it perfectly over the cold deepslate tiles. He took a deep breath and stepped onto it.

Thud.

Nothing. The wool compressed softly under his leather boot. The Skulk Sensor nearby didn't move an inch. Its tendrils stayed perfectly still.

Valen looked back at Elian and nodded. "It works. Stay on the carpet. Crouch low, and don't make a sound."

Side by side, the two inventors began their slow, agonizing journey toward the Central Plaza. They moved like ghosts through their own city. Every time the carpet ended, Valen would carefully place down another block of wool, creating a safe, silent path through the nightmare.

Through the shadows, they watched the tragedy of Luminos-Vara unfold. Citizens were hiding in their stone homes, barricading the doors with iron bars. But the iron bars rattled, and the rattling drew the monsters. Valen saw an Illager guard try to throw an iron axe at a Warden; the weapon missed, clattering loudly against the wall, and three Wardens instantly converged on the sound.

Valen wanted to scream, to help them, but Elian gripped his shoulder, shaking his head with tears in his eyes. The portal, Elian mouthed silently. Save the city.

They reached the edge of the Central Plaza.

The sight was breathtakingly horrifying. The Grand Gateway was no longer a monument of triumph; it looked like a giant, gaping mouth made of teeth and tendrils. The skulk had grown so thick around the frame that it formed giant, pulsing columns that stretched all the way to the cavern ceiling.

Right in front of the portal stood the biggest Warden Valen had ever seen—the very first one they had built, the one that had once bowed to him. Now, it was completely covered in bone-white plates, its chest pulsing with a dark, terrifying rhythm that shook the air itself.

And right at the base of the portal frame was the master control redstone line. To reach it, Valen would have to walk right past the monster’s feet.